<subSubSection pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="63.[151,1436,150,321]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,187,213]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sinclair &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2021" box="[820,879,187,212]" class="Insecta" genus="Iteaphila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incus">
<emphasis box="[820,879,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">incus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(anvil), in reference to the shape of the postgonites, and it is considered a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
